    <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_4_1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\vu = 2\vi + \vj</m> and <m>\vv = \vi + 2\vj</m> be vectors in <m>\R^3</m>.
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Without doing any computations, find a unit vector that is orthogonal to both <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>.  What does this tell you about the formula for <m>\vu \times \vv</m>?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Using the properties of the cross product and what you know about cross products involving the fundamental vectors <m>\vi</m> and <m>\vj</m>, compute <m>\vu \times \vv</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Next, use the determinant version of Equation<nbsp/><xref ref="E_9_4_cross_def"/> to compute <m>\vu \times \vv</m>.  Write one sentence that compares your results in (a), (b), and (c).
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Find the area of the parallelogram determined by <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <answer>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>c*\vk</m>. Since each vector lies in the xy-plane, a perpendicular vector will be in the z-direction.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vu \times \vv = 3\vk</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vu \times \vv = 3\vk</m>. The work in (b) and (c) confirm that the cross product will be a vector in the k-direction.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\Vert\vu \times \vv\Vert = 3</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>c*\vk</m>. Since each vector lies in the xy-plane, a perpendicular vector will be in the z-direction.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vu \times \vv = (2\vi + \vj) \times (\vi \times 2\vj) = 2(\vi \times \vi) + 4(\vi \times \vj) + (\vj \times \vi) + 2(\vj \times \vj) = 2(\vec{0}) + 4\vk + -1\vk + 2(\vec{0}) = 3\vk</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vu \times \vj = ((2)(0) - (2)(0))\vi - ((2)(0) - (1)(0))\vj + ((2)(2) - (1)(1))\vj = 0\vi + 0\vj + 3\vk = 3\vk</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The work in (b) and (c) confirm that the cross product will be a vector in the k-direction.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\Vert\vu \times \vv\Vert = \sqrt{(0)^2 + (0)^2 + (3)^2)} = \sqrt{9} = 3</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
      
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_4_2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\vx = \langle 1, 1, 1 \rangle</m> and <m>\vy = \langle 0, 3, -2 \rangle</m>.
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Are <m>\vx</m> and <m>\vy</m> orthogonal?  Are <m>\vx</m> and <m>\vy</m> parallel?  Clearly explain how you know, using appropriate vector products.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Find a unit vector that is orthogonal to both <m>\vx</m> and <m>\vy</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Express <m>\vy</m> as the sum of two vectors:  one parallel to <m>\vx</m>, the other orthogonal to <m>\vx</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Determine the area of the parallelogram formed by <m>\vx</m> and <m>\vy</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <answer>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vx</m> and <m>\vy</m> are not orthogonal because their dot product is not zero. <m>\vx</m> and <m>\vy</m> are not parallel because <m>\vx</m> is not a multiple of <m>\vy</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vu = \langle \frac{-5}{\sqrt{38}}, \frac{2}{\sqrt{38}}, \frac{3}{\sqrt{38}} \rangle</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vy = \langle \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3} \rangle + \langle \frac{-1}{3}, \frac{8}{3}, \frac{-7}{3} \langle</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\Vert\vx \times \vy\Vert = \sqrt{38}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vx \cdot \vy = (1)(0) + (1)(3) + (1)(-2) = 0 + 3 - 2 = 1</m>. The dot product is not zero so the two vectors are not orthogonal. <m>\vx</m> and <m>\vy</m> are not parallel because <m>\vx</m> is not a multiple of <m>\vy</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vx \times \vy = ((1)(-2) - (3)(1))\vi - ((1)(-2) - (1)(0))\vj + ((1)(3) - (1)(0))\vk = -5\vi + 2\vj + 3\vk</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>\Vert\vx \times \vy\Vert = \sqrt{(-5)^2 + (2)^2 + (3)^2} = \sqrt{38}</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>\vu = \langle \frac{-5}{\sqrt{38}}, \frac{2}{\sqrt{38}}, \frac{3}{\sqrt{38}} \rangle</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vy = \proj_{\vx}\vy + \proj_{\perp\vx}\vy</m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                <m>\proj_{\vx}\vy = \frac{\vy \cdot \vx}{\vx \cdot \vx} \vx = \frac{1}{3} * \langle 1, 1, 1 \rangle = \langle \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3} \rangle</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>\langle 0, 3, -2 \rangle = \langle \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3} \rangle + \proj_{\perp\vx}\vy</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>\proj_{\perp\vx}\vy = \langle \frac{-1}{3}, \frac{8}{3}, \frac{-7}{3} \rangle</m>. 
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>\vy = \langle \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3} \rangle + \langle \frac{-1}{3}, \frac{8}{3}, \frac{-7}{3} \rangle</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The area of the parallelogram is the magnitude of the cross product. <m>\Vert\vx \times \vy\Vert = \sqrt{(-5)^2 + (2)^2 + (3)^2}  = \sqrt{38}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
      
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_4_3">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the triangle in <m>\R^3</m> formed by <m>P(3, 2, -1)</m>, <m>Q(1, -2, 4)</m>, and <m>R(4, 4, 0)</m>.
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Find <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{PR}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Observe that the area of <m>\triangle PQR</m> is half of the area of the parallelogram formed by <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{PR}</m>.  Hence find the area of <m>\triangle PQR</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Find a unit vector that is orthogonal to the plane that contains points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Determine the measure of <m>\angle QPR</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <answer>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\overrightarrow{PQ} = \langle -2, -4, 5 \rangle</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{PR} = \langle 1, 2, 1 \rangle</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The area of <m>\triangle PQR = \frac{\sqrt{245}}{2}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\vu = \langle \frac{-14}{\sqrt{245}}, \frac{7}{\sqrt{245}}, 0 \rangle</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\angle PQR = 17.38^{\circ}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\overrightarrow{PQ} = \langle (1 - 3), (2 - (-2)), (-1 - 4) \rangle = \langle -2, -4, 5 \rangle</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{PR} = \langle (4 - 3), (4 - 2), (0 - (-1)) = \langle 1, 2, 1 \rangle</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The area of the parallelogram formed by <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{PR}</m> is the magnitude of the cross product <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{PQ} \times \overrightarrow{PR}\Vert = \Vert((-4)(1) - (2)(5))\vi - ((-2)(1) - (5)(1))\vj + ((-2)(2) - (-4)(1))\vk\Vert = \Vert-14\vi + 7\vj + 0\vk\Vert = \sqrt{(-14)^2 + (7)^2} = \sqrt{245}</m>. The area of <m>\triangle PQR = \frac{\sqrt{245}}{2}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\langle -14, 7, 0 \rangle</m> is orthogonal to the plan containing P, Q, and R. The unit vector in this direction is <m>\vu = \langle \frac{-14}{\sqrt{245}}, \frac{7}{\sqrt{245}}, 0 \rangle</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\overrightarrow{QP} = \langle 2, 4, -5 \rangle</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{QR} = \langle 3, 6, -4 \rangle</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{QP}\Vert = \sqrt{(2)^2 + (4)^2 + (-5)^2} = \sqrt{45} </m> and <m>\Vert\overrightarrow{QR}\Vert = \sqrt{(3)^2 + (6)^2 + (-4)^2} = \sqrt{61}</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>\theta = \cos^-1(\frac{\overrightarrow{QP} \cdot \overrightarrow{QR}}{\Vert\overrightarrow{QP}\Vert\Vert\overrightarrow{QR}\Vert} = \cos^-1(\frac{(2)(3) + (4)(6) + (-5)(-4)}{\sqrt{45}\sqrt{61}}) = 17.38^{\circ}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
      
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_4_distribute">
      <statement>
        <p>
           One of the properties of the cross product is that <m>(\vu+\vv) \times \vw = (\vu \times \vw) + (\vv \times \vw)</m>. That is, the cross product distributes over vector addition <em>on the right</em>. Here we investigate whether the cross product distributes over vector addition <em>on the left</em>. 

          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>\vu = \langle 1,2,-1 \rangle</m>, <m>\vv = \langle 4,-3,6 \rangle</m>, and <m>\vw = \langle 4,7,2 \rangle</m>. Calculate
                <me>
                  \vu \times (\vv + \vw) \ \ \text{ and } \ \ (\vu \times \vv) + (\vu \times \vw).
                </me>
                What do you notice?  
              </p>
            </li>
            
            <li>
              <p>
                Use the properties of the cross product to show that in general 
                <me>
                    \vx \times (\vy + \vz) = (\vx \times \vy) + (\vx \times \vz)
                </me>
                for any vectors <m>\vx</m>, <m>\vy</m>, and <m>\vz</m> in <m>\R^3</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <answer>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                 We get <m>20\vi - 16\vj - 12\vk</m> for both.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Using property 1, <m>\vx \times (\vy + \vz) = - ((\vy + \vz) \times \vx)</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                Using property 2, <m>- ((\vy + \vz) \times \vx) = - ((\vy \times \vx) + (\vz \times \vx))</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                Distribute -1 to get <m>-(\vy \times \vx) + -(\vz \times \vx)</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                Using property 1, <m>(\vx \times \vy) + (\vx \times \vz)</m>. 
              </p>

              <p>
                Therefore, for any vectors <m>\vx</m>, <m>\vy</m>, and <m>\vz</m> in <m>\R^3</m>, <m>\vx \times (\vy + \vz) = (\vx \times \vy) + (\vx \times \vz)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate the left side: <m>\vu + \vw = \langle 8, 4, 8 \rangle</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                Then <m>\langle 1, 2, 1 \rangle \times \langle 8, 4, 8 \rangle = ((2)(8) - (-1)(4))\vi - ((1)(8) - (-1)(8))\vj + ((1)(4) - (2)(8))\vj = \langle 20, -16, -12 \rangle</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                Calculate the right side: <m>\vu \times \vv = ((2)(6) - (-1)(3))\vi - ((1)(6) - (-1)(4))\vj + ((1)(-3) - (2)(4))\vj = \langle 9, -10, -11 \rangle</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                And <m>\vu \times \vw = ((2)(2) - (-1)(7))\vi - ((1)(2) - (-1)(4))\vj + ((1)(7) - (2)(4))\vj = \langle 11, -6, -1 \rangle</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                Then <m>\vu \times \vv + \vu \times \vw = \langle 20, -16, -12</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                Therefore, the two expressions are equal.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                See answer above.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>

    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_4_4">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\vu = \langle u_1, u_2, u_3 \rangle</m>, <m>\vv = \langle v_1, v_2, v_3 \rangle</m>, and <m>\vw = \langle w_1, w_2, w_3 \rangle</m> be vectors in <m>\R^3</m>. In this exercise we investigate properties of the triple scalar product <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw</m>. 
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw = \left|\begin{array}{ccc}
                u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3 \\
                v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3 \\
                w_1 \amp w_2 \amp w_3
                \end{array} \right| </m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Show that <m>\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
                u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3 \\
                v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3 \\
                w_1 \amp w_2 \amp w_3
                \end{array} \right|  = -\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
                v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3 \\
                u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3 \\
                w_1 \amp w_2 \amp w_3
                \end{array} \right|</m>. Conclude that interchanging the first two rows in a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix changes the sign of the determinant. In general (although we won't show it here), interchanging any two rows in a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix changes the sign of the determinant.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Use the results of parts (a) and (b) to argue that 
                <me> 
                  (\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw = (\vw \times \vu) \cdot \vv = (\vv \times \vw) \cdot \vu.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Now suppose that <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vw</m> do not lie in a plane when they eminate from a common initial point. 
                <ol marker="i.">
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Given that the parallepiped determined by <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vw</m> must have positive volume, what can we say about <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw</m>?
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Now suppose that <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vw</m> all lie in the same plane. What value must <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw</m> have? Why?
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Explain how (i.) and (ii.) show that if <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vw</m> all eminate from the same initial point, then <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vw</m> lie in the same plane if and only if <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw = 0</m>. This provides a straightforward  computational method for determining when three vectors are co-planar. 
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate the left side: <m>(\vu \times \vv) = (u_2v_3 - u_3v_2)\vi + (u_1v_3 - u_3v_1)\vj + (u_1v_2 - u_2v_1)\vk</m>.
              </p>
  
              <p>
                Then <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw = ((u_2v_3 - u_3v_2)\vi - (u_1v_3 - u_3v_1)\vj + (u_1v_2 - u_2v_1)\vk) \cdot \langle w_1, w_2, w_3 \rangle = w_1(u_2v_3 - u_3v_2) - w_2(u_1v_3 - u_3v_1) + w_3(u_1v_2 - u_2v_1) = u_2v_3w_1 - u_3v_2w_1 - u_1v_3w_2 + u_3v_1w_2 + u_1v_2w_3 - u_2v_1w_3</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                Calculate the right side: the determinant of the 3x3 matrix using technology is <m>u_3(v_1w_2 - v_2w_1) + u_2(v_3w_1 - v_1w_3) + u_1(v_2w_3 - v_3w_2) = u_3v_1w_2 - u_3v_2w_1 + u_2v_3w_1 - u_2v_1w_3 + u_1v_3w_3 - u_1v_3w_2</m>. We can reorder to get <m>u_2v_3w_1 - u_3v_2w_1 - u_1v_3w_2 + u_3v_1w_2 + u_1v_2w_3 - u_2v_1w_3</m>. Therefore, these expressions are equal.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate the right side: the determinant of the 3x3 matrix using technology is <m>u_3(v_2w_1 - v_1w_2) + u_2(v_1w_3 - v_3w_1) + u_1(v_3w_2 - v_2w_3) = u_3v_2w_1 - u_3v_1w_2 + u_2v_1w_3 - u_2v_3w_1 + u_1v_3w_2 - u_1v_2w_3 = -(u_3v_1w_2 - u_3v_2w_1 + u_2v_3w_1 - u_2v_1w_3 + u_1v_3w_3 - u_1v_3w_2)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
               <p>
                 <m>(\vw \times \vu) \cdot \vv = \left|\begin{array}{ccc}
                   w_1 \amp  w_2 \amp w_3 \\
                   u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3 \\
                   v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3
                   \end{array} \right| = -\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
                   u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3 \\
                   w_1 \amp  w_2 \amp w_3 \\
                   v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3
                   \end{array} \right| = - (-\left|\begin{array}{ccc})
                   u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3 \\
                   v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3 \\
                   w_1 \amp  w_2 \amp w_3
                   \end{array} \right| = (\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw
                 </m>
               </p>

                <p>
                  <m>(\vv \times \vw) \cdot \vu = \left|\begin{array}{ccc}
                    v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3 \\
                    w_1 \amp  w_2 \amp w_3 \\
                    u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3
                    \end{array} \right| = -\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
                    v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3 \\
                    u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3 \\
                    w_1 \amp  w_2 \amp w_3
                    \end{array} \right| = - (-\left|\begin{array}{ccc})
                    u_1 \amp  u_2 \amp u_3 \\
                    v_1 \amp  v_2 \amp v_3 \\
                    w_1 \amp  w_2 \amp w_3
                    \end{array} \right| = (\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw
                  </m>.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
               <ol marker="i.">
                 <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw</m> must be positive.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                 <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw = 0</m>. The cross product of <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> is a vector perpendicular to both. If <m>\vw</m> lies in the same plane as <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>, then the cross product of <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> will also be perpendicular to <m>\vw</m>. The dot product between perpendicular vectors is <m>0</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                 <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vw</m> do not lie in the same plane, then <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw</m> is positive. The only time that <m>(\vu \times \vv) \cdot \vw = 0</m> is if <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vw</m> all lie in the same plane.
                   </p>
                 </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="verifycrossortho">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In <xref ref="geocross" />, we stated <q>Because the cross product works well with linear combinations, <m>\vu\times\vv</m> is perpendicular to any linear combination of <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>.</q> We want to verify this algebraically here; Specifically, show that <m>\vu\times\vv</m> will be orthogonal to any vector of the form <m>a\vu+b\vv</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>(\vu\times\vv)\cdot(a\vu+b\vv)=a[(\vu\times\vv)\cdot\vu] + b[(\vu\times\vv)\cdot\vv] = a [0]+b[0]</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>(\vu\times\vv)\cdot(a\vu+b\vv)=a[(\vu\times\vv)\cdot\vu] + b[(\vu\times\vv)\cdot\vv] = a [0]+b[0]</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>  
